                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Your entire post assumes that guilds will continue to function on raids as they do now.  You have made a bad assumption.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Belanar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Eh, points 1, 2 and 4 are silly. The position of "raid leader" in the game is just a designation within the raid grouping system. Quite often it isn't the same as the person actually leading the raid. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
As described, the abilities of the raid leader are the ones that the raid can use.  And they are used *by the raid leader*.  You say the person leading the raid is not the raid leader.  Guess what?  They have to be.  If I am going to use a raid leader skill, I have to have the skill and I have to be raid leader.  It is *not* "just a designation."  At least, not anymore.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Belanar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I have never heard anyone say, "wow, I wish I was the 'raid leader' just once. That would be so great". In fact most people try to hand off the title as it mostly means "person who has to find and /raidinvite newcomers". The "raid leader" in EQ raids is more like "club secretary" or something.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
You really need to distinguish between the tag and the function.  Yes, in that past, the person truly leading the raid often did not have the tag.  Yeah, in the past, who had raid leadership didn't matter a damn.  However, they will have to have it in the future.  If you insist in not thinking about how the skills will affect future raids, refrain from calling anyone else's thoughts on the matter "silly."
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Belanar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Point 3 is the biggest problem imo. A wise guild might always designate a guild-owned character that anyone can log in as the permanent "raid leader".</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
And designing features that encourage the violation of your license agreement is good design?  Yeah, you can get around it and we most likely will.  Suggesting that we can get around poor game design doesn't eliminate the fact that it is poor game design.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Belanar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Point 5 is cause Sony wants to make you work for new features as they can't think of enough new skills to give people that wouldn't be overpowering... Yeah, it's lame, but it's designed to keep people playing.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Who does it keep playing?  That one guy that owns the account that is designated as the raid leader?  what does it do to keep the other 35-70 people playing in that guild?  Not a whole hell of alot.  This is a feature for 1 character in an entire guild, and only for high level guilds at that.  
<br />

<br />
My entire premise is that this is bad game design.  I stand by that premise.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Oznoyng Castintank, Coercer of Inner Circle, Xegony
<br />
E65.223/Xg h-- 5272hp 6480mp ft25 G++++!! e++++ o++ T++ L H+++ f g !b c+++ t++++ D+</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
